<p class="lead"><strong>Just like in Word Processing, the date can be inserted into your spreadsheet and automatically updated every time you open or print the document.</strong></p class="lead">
	

<p>If asked to insert the date and the time, you can select a format that includes the time.</p>

<p>First, you click on the cell where you want to insert the date and/or time in your spreadsheet. </p>

<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/formulaicon.jpg"/>

<p>Next, you click on the <strong><i>fx</i></strong> function icon next to the Formula Bar space and the <strong>Insert Function Box</strong> will appear. </p>

<p>In the space below <strong>Search for a function</strong> type in:
<strong>"current date"</strong> and click on the <strong>Go</strong> button.

<p>In the functions that appear in the <strong>Select a Function</strong> space, choose <strong>"Today"</strong> and click <strong>OK</strong>.
<br />
<br />



<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/insertcurrentdate.jpg"/>



<p>After inserting the function, you will see the function in the formula bar. Next, you can select the format of the date. Below you can see the user has inserted a date and the function can be seen in the formula bar.</p>

<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/currentdateexample.jpg"/>

<hr>
<p>The next step is to select the format you want for the date. You can make this selection in the <strong>Format Cells Box</strong>. Accessing this box depends on your version.</p>

